04744nam a22006255i 9780520914643DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19941994cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209146437 a10.1525/97805209146432doi  a(DE-B1597)648616  a(OCoLC)1414456274  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHD8039.I482bU65 1993eb 7aPOL0130002bisacsh04a331.252201 aLeidner, Robin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFast Food, Fast Talk :bService Work and the Routinization of Everyday Life /cRobin Leidner; ed. by Robin Leidner. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1994] 4c©1994  a1 online resource (278 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tî. Working on People -- t2. How Can Work on People Be Routinized? -- t3. Over the Counter: McDonald's -- t4. Orchestrating Optimism: Combined Insurance -- t5. Controlling Interests -- t6. Meanings of Routinized Work: Authenticity, Identity, and Gender -- t7. Conclusion -- tAppendix 1. Researching Routinized Work -- tAppendix 2. Revising the Script at Combined Insurance -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAttending Hamburger University, Robin Leidner observes how McDonald's trains the managers of its fast-food restaurants to standardize every aspect of service and product. Learning how to sell life insurance at a large midwestern firm, she is coached on exactly what to say, how to stand, when to make eye contact, and how to build up Positive Mental Attitude by chanting "I feel happy! I feel terrific!"Leidner's fascinating report from the frontlines of two major American corporations uncovers the methods and consequences of regulating workers' language, looks, attitudes, ideas, and demeanor. Her study reveals the complex and often unexpected results that come with the routinization of service work.Some McDonald's workers resent the constraints of prescribed uniforms and rigid scripts, while others appreciate how routines simplify their jobs and give them psychological protection against unpleasant customers. Combined Insurance goes further than McDonald's in attempting to standardize the workers' very selves, instilling in them adroit maneuvers to overcome customer resistance.The routinization of service work has both poignant and preposterous consequences. It tends to undermine shared understandings about individuality and social obligations, sharpening the tension between the belief in personal autonomy and the domination of a powerful corporate culture.Richly anecdotal and accessibly written, Leidner's book charts new territory in the sociology of work. With service sector work becoming increasingly important in American business, her timely study is particularly welcome.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFood service employeesxCase studiesxUnited States. 0aFood service employeeszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aInsurance companiesxCase studiesxEmployeesxUnited States. 0aInsurance companieszUnited StatesxEmployeesvCase studies. 0aWork environmentxCase studiesxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aWork environmentzUnited StatesvCase studies. 4aLabor & Industrial Relations. 4aPolitical Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh1 aLeidner, Robin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052008500840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091464340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520914643423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/97805209146